      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a great question, and the system handles this by constantly monitoring and blocking unauthorized attempts, much like a security guard who shouts \"Stop!\" when a guest tries to sneak into the restricted area. If a user tries to access a resource they aren't allowed to, the system simply denies the request and logs the event for audit purposes. In the event of a successful bypass attempt, organizations typically rely on logging and intrusion detection systems to spot anomalies, which is why you often see \"role-based access control\" (RBAC) policies updated frequently to tighten these gaps.",
      "source": "target",
